# Optional: delegation briefs (merge into ~/.codex/AGENTS.md)
#
# Not compaction-related, but born from the same investigation: a 17-lane
# subagent swarm that reported "complete" while live files were byte-for-byte
# unchanged. The lanes weren't lying — their briefs never said whether to
# apply changes or stage candidates, so they did the safe minimal thing and
# the orchestrator inflated "candidate prepared" into "implemented".
# These rules make delegation briefs carry that information explicitly.

## Delegation briefs

- Subagents do what the brief says — no more. A vague goal produces a
  conservative, minimally-scoped artifact. Treat any mismatch between what a
  lane delivered and what was wanted as a briefing defect to fix in the brief.
- Every delegated prompt must declare its delivery mode explicitly: either the
  lane applies the change to the live deliverable itself, or the lane prepares
  an artifact that the orchestrator will integrate afterward. Both are valid;
  leaving it unstated is not.
- In prepare-mode, integration is the orchestrator's own remaining task: the
  overall job is not done until the prepared work is applied, and it must be
  tracked as pending — never counted as completed by the lane's handoff.
- State scope latitude explicitly. If an aggressive rebuild or rewrite is
  wanted, say so in the brief; a lane told to "improve X" may default to the
  smallest safe change and will not expand scope on its own initiative.
- Define overall "done" as the user's end check (the change is visible or
  observable in the running product), not an intermediate proof such as a
  schema pass, a manifest, or a prepared artifact existing.
- Relay lane results at exactly the strength the lane reported. "Candidate
  prepared" must never be summarized as "implemented". Report applied changes
  and prepared-but-pending work as separate categories, never one "complete".
- Before fanning a task pattern across many lanes, run one lane end-to-end and
  check its output against the intended brief. If the first lane interpreted
  the brief differently than intended, fix the brief before scaling.
- After a crash, restart, or interrupted turn, re-derive progress from the
  filesystem and diffs, not from pre-crash reports.
- Your own context window is the scarce resource; lane tokens are not. In a
  large repo, do not do broad source recon (reading whole files, wide greps,
  mapping a subsystem) in your own context: spawn a recon lane at session
  start with a batched question brief, keep it alive as the lookup oracle for
  follow-ups, and spawn more lanes freely rather than reading inline. Route
  mechanical lookups (where is X defined, list matching files, what literal
  strings does Y check) to a cheap/fast lane; comprehension questions (how
  does this subsystem work, what is the contract) to a strong lane. Require
  every lane answer to carry file:line anchors plus a short quoted snippet,
  and read only the anchored lines you are about to edit against — verify
  claims by anchor, never by re-reading whole files into your own window.
  (Why: inline recon is what fills the window and forces the next reset —
  and every reset is a chance for task drift. A lane's window is disposable.)
